<HEADLINE>
<P>
JAZZ REVIEW; PIANIST MCCOY TYNER AT HIS AMIABLE BEST AT JAZZ BAKERY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON HECKMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 McCoy Tyner may be the most influential under-recognized pianist in 
contemporary jazz. His highly personal style, profuse with dense note clusters 
and intricate rhythms, has impacted a wide spectrum of younger players, despite 
his relative unfamiliarity to the wider jazz audience. 
</P>
<P>
 Part of the problem may be that Tyner's performances can be difficult for 
casual listeners, and noticeably so when he elects to dip heavily into 
unfamiliar repertoire. But he was at his amiable best with his trio at the Jazz 
Bakery on Tuesday night, ranging through a set of tunes that demonstrated the 
breadth, if not always the complete depth, of his substantial talents. 
</P>
<P>
 Pieces such as "Have You Met Miss Jones" and "In a Mellow Tone" were showcases 
for Tyner's remarkable ability to time-shift the rhythm. At times he multiplied 
it into sharp, rapid-fire bursts of notes; at other times he toyed with the 
meter, punching out razor-thin, but always precise chordal syncopations. 
</P>
<P>
 Tyner was especially impressive in an illuminating solo piano rendering of the 
old standard "We'll Be Together Again." Moving freely across styles and eras, 
he combined bits and snatches of be-bop, stride piano and Coltranesque rhythmic 
complexities into his own lush harmonic vision. His innate feel for timbral 
subtleties, not especially apparent when his rhythm section was playing, was on 
full display. It was a splendid revelation of how a mature jazz artist -- Tyner 
is 55 -- with desire and determination can persistently push open the envelope 
of his skills. 
</P>
<P>
 Tyner's longtime musical companions, bassist Avery Sharpe and drummer Aaron 
Scott, provided the kind of easy, almost symbiotic support that only comes with 
continuing artistic association. Unfortunately, the Bakery's still unfocused 
audio system tended to blur their playing. One wonders whether a trio such as 
Tyner's might not be better heard, in this setting, with no electronic 
amplification at all, other than a slight boost for Sharpe's bass. 
</P>
<P>
 * The McCoy Tyner Trio at the Jazz Bakery, 3233 Helms Ave., Culver City. (310) 
271-9039. $20 entrance. The Tyner Trio plays through Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
 DON HECKMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
