<HEADLINE>
<P>
BATTLE OF GOALIES STAYS CLOSE IN DUCKS' TIE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBYN NORWOOD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Guy Hebert is still the only Mighty Duck with his own ESPN SportsCenter 
highlight, but he has competition for the No. 1 goaltending job. 
</P>
<P>
 Mikhail Shtalenkov played the whole way in the Ducks' 1-1 tie with San Jose in 
a neutral-site exhibition at McNichols Arena on Wednesday, and the goal he 
allowed was one Coach Ron Wilson said he would have questioned if there had 
been video-replay capability. 
</P>
<P>
 "I respect Mike as much as I do Guy," Wilson said. "Whoever plays best will be 
in there. Mike established himself last year and from here out, they'll be 
alternated to see who starts opening night. 
</P>
<P>
 "If one's not clearly better than the other, I'll maybe 1-A and 1-B them." 
</P>
<P>
 Rookie Paul Kariya was held pointless but set up some outstanding scoring 
chances. 
</P>
<P>
 Peter Douris scored for the Ducks (0-2-1), who play their first home 
exhibition Sunday against Vancouver. ROBYN NORWOOD 
</P>
</TEXT>
