<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; FLORIDA; ONLY 4 CUBANS PICKED UP AT SEA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 U.S. Coast Guard troops had seen only four Cuban refugees in the Florida 
Straits by midafternoon Wednesday, one day after the Cuban government began to 
crack down on departures by sea. A spokesman in Miami for the Coast Guard said 
144 Cubans were picked up amid high winds and waves on Tuesday, after the Cuban 
government, which reached an immigration accord with the United States, began 
to stop homemade rafts, inner tubes and flimsy boats from leaving the 
island.Cuban beaches were reported clear of the rafters. Despite the drop in 
rescues, the Coast Guard has no plans to recall the dozens of vessels that have 
been searching for refugees over the past month, the spokesman said. Coast 
Guard cutters and U.S. Navy ships have intercepted 37,046 Cuban refugees so far 
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
