<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: GARDENA; CARD CLUB EXPANSION FACES COUNCIL VOTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN WOODWARD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council is expected to vote Sept. 27 on a proposed ordinance to 
double the number of card tables allowed in Gardena's two card clubs. 
</P>
<P>
 The change in the city code was requested by Councilman Mas Fukai, who said he 
heard rumors that the state wanted to limit the number of card clubs throughout 
California, City Manager Kenneth W. Landau said. 
</P>
<P>
 "This gives us the opportunity to allow the two existing clubs in the city to 
expand, if they want to," Landau said. 
</P>
<P>
 The two clubs -- the El Dorado at Redondo Beach Boulevard and Vermont Avenue 
and the Normandie Club on Rosecrans Avenue -- contribute a combined $5 million 
a year to the city, Landau said. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the new ordinance, each club could have 250 tables for poker and Asian 
card games. SUSAN WOODWARD 
</P>
</TEXT>
