<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: SOUTH PASADENA; CITY ORDERED TO PAY EX-MAYOR'S LEGAL FEES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The city's bill in its legal battle against former Mayor Lee D. Prentiss has 
risen to nearly $1.8 million after a judge ordered the city to pay attorney's 
fees in the case. 
</P>
<P>
 Pasadena Superior Court Judge J. Michael Byrne last week ordered the city to 
pay $248,000 in legal fees accumulated by Prentiss in addition to an 
outstanding jury award of $1.2 million and more than $300,000 for its 
attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
 A jury awarded Prentiss the money in July after determining that city 
officials had violated Prentiss' civil rights in 1990 by conspiring to revoke a 
building permit to expand his 86-year-old home.  
</P>
<P>
 South Pasadena officials say the city does not have insurance to cover civil 
rights claims and will be forced to use up funds earmarked for emergencies and 
new equipment to cover the mounting bill. The almost $1.5 million owed is 
nearly 19% of the city's budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
