<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: THE REGION; WATER DISTRICT GETS $500,000 RECYCLING GRANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Upper San Gabriel Valley Municipal Water District has received a $500,000 
federal grant for a water recycling program. 
</P>
<P>
 The Water Recycle 2000 grant from the U.S. Department of the Interior will be 
used to implement a water reclamation project. 
</P>
<P>
 By using recycled water, the district will be able to rely less on imported 
water. The valley's water supply comes from three sources: natural rainfall and 
runoff, the Colorado River and the Sacramento Delta. But recent environmental 
policies have made imported water more expensive and less reliable. 
</P>
<P>
 The project's first phase is scheduled to begin in fall, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091594-0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 079473 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 15, 1994, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
South Bay; Part J; Page 9 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
